Overview
Fixed-time traffic signal plans cannot react to the volatile, non-stationary demand seen in modern cities. This project frames traffic signal control as a sequential decision-making problem where each intersection operates as an autonomous RL agent. Starting from a single-agent DQN baseline, we progressively integrate algorithmic enhancements to build a scalable, cooperative multi-agent system.
Best result: Dueling Double DQN with Prioritized Experience Replay (PER) achieves an average vehicle waiting time of 12.9 seconds, compared to 55.1 seconds under a random policy — a 76% reduction.

Architecture & Algorithms
