Key Components

CityFlow Simulator — Microscopic traffic simulator running ~20× faster than SUMO, wrapped in a Gym-compatible interface.
CTDE Framework — Centralized Training / Decentralized Execution: all agents share a single replay buffer during training but execute policies independently at runtime.
Double DQN — Separates action selection (online network) from action evaluation (target network) to reduce overestimation bias.
Dueling DQN — Decomposes Q-values into a state-value V(s) and an advantage A(s,a) for more stable learning.
Graph Attention Network (GAT) — Two stacked GAT convolutional layers build node embeddings that capture each intersection's local state and its neighbors' congestion patterns.
Neighbor-Aware Reward — Penalizes each agent for both its own queue and a weighted fraction of adjacent intersections' queues, driving cooperative "green wave" behavior.
Prioritized Experience Replay (PER) — Assigns sampling priority to transitions with large TD errors, accelerating learning from the most informative experiences.
Reward Normalization — Exponential moving average standardizes rewards to zero-mean/unit-variance, preventing destabilization from traffic spikes.
Gradient Clipping — Caps gradient norm at 1.0 to prevent exploding gradients from large TD errors.


Environment
The simulation runs on a 4×4 grid (16 signalised intersections) defined by three JSON files:

roadnet.json — Road network topology (intersections, lanes, connections)
flow.json — Vehicle definitions (speed, acceleration, routes, arrival intervals)
config.json — Entry point linking the above files and simulation parameters

Observation space: 72-dimensional vector per intersection (queued vehicle counts on incoming and outgoing lanes).
Action space: 9 discrete traffic light phases per intersection.
Reward: Negative sum of waiting times across all vehicles at an intersection (normalized during training).
Episode length: 1,000 steps at 1 Hz control frequency.

